🧠 Ultra-Short Memory Trick

DFS = Stack = Deep

BFS = Queue = Level

⚡ Code Flow in 1 Line

DFS:
visit → recurse → backtrack

BFS:
enqueue → process → enqueue neighbors

BFS (Breadth First Search)
--------------------------
Start → explore LEVEL → next level → repeat

Code Flow:
bfs(s):
  mark visited[s]
  enqueue(s)

  while queue not empty:
    u = dequeue()
    print(u)
    for each v in adj[u]:
      if not visited:
        mark visited[v]
        enqueue(v)

Key:
- Uses Queue (FIFO)
- Level-by-level
- Gives shortest path (unweighted)



DFS (Depth First Search)
------------------------
Start → go DEEP → backtrack → repeat

Code Flow:
dfs(u):
  mark visited[u]
  print(u)
  for each v in adj[u]:
    if not visited:
      dfs(v)

Key:
- Uses Recursion / Stack
- Path-focused
- Can go very deep first


⚡ Key Point (Very Important)

👉 v is NOT number of edges
👉 v is ONLY number of vertices (nodes)


When nodes are strings instead of integers, you can’t use direct indexing like adjList.get(0).
So you use a HashMap instead.

🔹 Key Idea

👉 Replace:

ArrayList<ArrayList<Integer>>

👉 With:

HashMap<String, ArrayList<String>>

